PortSwigger Web Security Academy Lab: DOM XSS in innerHTML Sink Using Source location.search

Lab Overview

Lab Name: DOM XSS in innerHTML sink using source location.search

Category: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)

Difficulty: Apprentice

Objective: Exploit a DOM-based XSS vulnerability caused by user-controlled input from "location.search" being inserted into the page using the "innerHTML" sink.

It is mentioned in lab description that the application contains a DOM-based Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerability. User-supplied data from the URL query string is retrieved via "location.search" and dynamically inserted into the page using the "innerHTML" property.

Source

location.search

Sink

element.innerHTML


The search functionality was examined by supplying various inputs through the search parameter.

Example:

/search?search=123

The search term appeared dynamically within the page. Inspecting the page source and browser Developer Tools revealed JavaScript similar to:

document.getElementById("searchMessage").innerHTML =
  "Results for: " + searchTerm;

This indicated that user-controlled input from "location.search" was being written directly into the DOM using "innerHTML".

Exploitation

An initial payload using a "<script>" tag did not execute because browsers generally prevent script execution when inserted through "innerHTML".

Payload tested:

<script>alert(1)</script>

To bypass this behavior we used an event-handler-based payload was used:

<img src=1 onerror=alert(1)>

How it worked:
1. The application reads the search parameter from the URL.
2. The value is inserted into the page using "innerHTML".
3. The browser parses the injected HTML and creates an image element.
4. The image source is invalid.
5. The "onerror" event triggers automatically.
6. JavaScript executes via "alert(1)".

Proof of Exploitation

When the crafted URL was loaded, a JavaScript alert box appeared, confirming successful execution of attacker-controlled code within the application's origin.

This demonstrated a successful DOM-based XSS attack and completed the lab objective.

Impact

A successful DOM XSS vulnerability can enable an attacker to:

- Hijack authenticated user sessions.
- Steal sensitive information.
- Modify page content.
- Perform actions on behalf of logged-in users.

Root Cause

The vulnerability exists because untrusted user input flows directly from a DOM source into a dangerous HTML-rendering sink.

Unsafe data flow:

location.search → innerHTML → DOM XSS

The application fails to sanitize or encode user input before inserting it into the page.

Remediation

1. Avoid innerHTML for Untrusted Data

Use safer alternatives such as:

element.textContent = userInput;

or

element.innerText = userInput;

instead of:

element.innerHTML = userInput;

2. Sanitize User Input

If HTML rendering is required, sanitize user-controlled content before insertion.

3. Context-Aware Output Encoding

Encode data according to the context in which it is rendered.

4. Implement Content Security Policy (CSP)

Deploy a restrictive CSP to reduce the impact of XSS vulnerabilities.

Example:

Content-Security-Policy:
default-src 'self';
script-src 'self';

Conclusion

The application was vulnerable to DOM-based Cross-Site Scripting because user-controlled data from "location.search" was inserted directly into the DOM using "innerHTML". By injecting a malicious HTML element containing an event handler, arbitrary JavaScript execution was achieved. The vulnerability can be mitigated by avoiding "innerHTML" for untrusted data, implementing proper sanitization and encoding, and deploying a strong Content Security Policy.